        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>In the Rev. Mr. Morais&#39; reply to  Yours&#91;&#63;&#93;&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>he says there is no mention made in the<lb/> Bible of Prayers for the dead&#44;  but that is<lb/> found in the book of Maccabees&#44; we do not<lb/> believe that the Apochryphia is inspired&#91;.&#93;<lb/> Consequently it is not part of our Bible<lb/> nor is it bound up in it&#44; however I got a<lb/> Roman Catholic Bible and found<lb/> what Mr. Morais eludes to&#91;.&#93; we con&#45;<lb/>sider that when the Lord takes<lb/> our dear ones to  himself&#44; they no longer<lb/> require our prayers&#44; &#34;as the tree falls so shall<lb/>lie&#34;¬ù&#45;&#45; we of course do not believe as the<lb/> Romanists do that there is an intermediate<lb/> state. Regarding the shedding of <lb/> blood for the remission of sins&#44; Mr. <sic>Marais</sic><lb/> says it never was a dogma in the Jewish<lb/> Church&#44; that the blood of Animals was<lb/>  intended as an atonement for sins.<lb/> This astonishes me very much&#44; for who<lb/> can read the 16<hi rend="sup">th</hi> &#38; 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Chapters of<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Leviticus  &#38; not believe that these animals<lb/> were offered as an atonement The 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> &#38;16<lb/> verses of the 16<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Ch&#91;apter&#93;. For instance&#44; then the<lb/> 11<hi rend="sup">th</hi> ver. of the 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Ch. says&#44; for the life<lb/> of the flesh is in the blood&#44; &#38; I have given <lb/> it to you as your Altar to make an<lb/> atone<hi rend="underline">m</hi>ent <hi rend="underline">for</hi> <hi rend="underline">your</hi> <hi rend="underline">souls</hi>. For it is the<lb/> <hi rend="underline">blood</hi> that makes an <hi rend="underline">atonement</hi> <hi rend="underline">for</hi><lb/> the <hi rend="underline">soul</hi>&#44; what can be more comprehensive<lb/> The reason why you do not eat the blood<lb/> in your meat&#58; is&#44; because it <hi rend="underline">was</hi> <hi rend="underline">used</hi> for<lb/> an atonement for your souls&#44; now&#44; since<lb/> you no longer use the  blood as an atonement<lb/> why not let the blood remain in the meat&#45;&#45;<lb/> it seems to me if the one is given up&#44; why<lb/> not the other&#44; the one was as strictly<lb/>commanded as the other.<lb/></p>
            <p>The quotation from Hosea&#44; I do not<lb/> quite understand. &#34;One may pay for<lb/> <hi rend="underline">Steers</hi>&#91;&#63;&#93; by the utterance of our lips&#34;¬ù<lb/> Now his quotation from Hosea Ch. 1&#91;overwritten&#58;5&#93;4<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>&#38; 2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> Ver. reads thus &#34;say unto the &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> take away all iniquity and receive<lb/> us graciously so will we render the<lb/> calves of our lips.&#34;¬ù &#38; Scott. one of<lb/> the best Commentators <sic>interperates</sic><lb/> the verse thus&#44; Israel is here exhorted to<lb/> return to the Lord &#38; they might expect<lb/> all blessings promised their Fathers&#45;&#45;<lb/> &#34;Then with their lips they would proclaim<lb/> his praise&#44; rendering him sacrifices<lb/> of Thanksgiving&#44; far more acceptable<lb/> than the blood of the calves of the stall&#34;¬ù<lb/> Another question I would like to ask.<lb/> <hi rend="underline">When</hi> &#38; <hi rend="underline">How</hi> is the Messiah the Savior<lb/> to come&#45;&#45; as is promised in The Old<lb/> Testament. how about the 53<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> ch. of  Isaiah&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>From Mrs. L. Robertson<lb/>
                to<lb/>
                Rev. Mr. S. Morais.<lb/>
                New York April 1884.<lb/></p>
        </body>
